<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-876-046  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 876 046.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  Oct 1989 v22 n10 p89(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Medical symposium looks at regulation of computer-based systems.andO;(the second IEEE Symposium on Computer-based Medical Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Margaret.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The second IEEE Symposium on Computer-Based Medical Systems inMinneapolis in late Jun 1989 discussed the regulation and approvalprocess in terms of the safety and reliability of computer-basedmedical instruments.andP;  Keynote speaker James Howard of GeneralElectric spoke on 'Computer-Based Medicine: The Opportunity andthe Challenge', while consultant Ruth Dayhoff, the other keynotespeaker, addressed 'Software Quality: The Problem of Proof'.andP;  Theevolution of regulations, safety and hazards from the early X-raysto nuclear magnetic imaging was described by Howard; he pointedout that US Food and Drug Administration approval of medicalinstruments now emphasizes paperwork and often increases cost.andO;Dayhoff used the example of the recent disaster in which anairliner was destroyed by a missile controlled by the Aegis shipdefense system to discuss computer-system problems.andP;  Several otherspeakers and tutorials at the symposium are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Medical LaboratoriesRegulationInstrumentsSoftware QualityHealth CareSeminarsReliabilityIEEE Symposium on Computer-Based Medical Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>